08 - publication quality plots using ggplot

Jenny Bigman

5/12/2022

Lets learn how to modify a plot to make it ready for publication in a journal. The theme() function has endless arguments you can call to customize your plot. There are built-in themes (we have used one, theme_classic(), but you can also modify (probably) any component. Look here: https://ggplot2.tidyverse.org/reference/theme.html. Keep in mind, not all modifcations will be in the theme function.

Lets work with the plot we saved from the last exercise and start with a few simple modifications. Weve already learned how to rename our axes, but lets work on formatting them.

mem_plot1 

# we want log10 to show up as log(subscript 10)

# many ways to do this, here's one

x_lab <- expression(paste(log[10], " wing length")) 
# why the extra space before wing
y_lab <- expression(paste(log[10], " beak height"))

# if you wanted to do a superscript instead
#super <- expression(paste(x^{10}, " x wing length"))

    mem_plot1 +
        labs(x = x_lab, y = y_lab)

Lets modify components of the theme. To do so, you will specify an argument (e.g., axis.title()) and then specify an element (e.g., element_line(), element_rect(), element_text(), or element_blank()). Which of these elements you use depends on the argument. For example, if you want to modify the size of text, this is a text element (use element_text()). Then, youd fill in a few more arguments (e.g., size = 16). If you dont want a given component (axis labels, panel.grid, etc) use element_blank() (with nothing in the parentheses). You can also specify which axis you want to change if you do not want to change both (e.g., axis.line.x = element_line() will change the x axis and axis.line = element_line() will change both). Lets play around with this.

    mem_plot1 +
        labs(x = x_lab, y = y_lab) +
        theme(
            axis.title = element_text(size = 14, color = "grey50"),
            panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
            panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
            panel.background = element_rect(fill = "transparent"),
        plot.background = element_rect(fill = "transparent", color = NA),
            axis.line.x = element_line(color = "grey50"))

# both axes, black background, white text
    mem_plot1 +
        labs(x = x_lab, y = y_lab) +
        theme(
            axis.title = element_text(size = 14, color = "white"),
            axis.ticks = element_line(color = "white"),
            axis.text = element_text(size = 12, color = "white"),
            axis.line = element_line(color = "white"),
            panel.grid = element_blank(),
            panel.background = element_rect(fill = "black"),
        plot.background = element_rect(fill = "black"))

Lets deal with the legend. Even though the legend is in the theme section, it works a little differently. To remove it, you specify legend.position = "none".

    mem_plot1 +
        labs(x = x_lab, y = y_lab) +
        theme(
            axis.title = element_text(size = 14, color = "white"),
            axis.ticks = element_line(color = "white"),
            axis.text = element_text(size = 12, color = "white"),
            axis.line = element_line(color = "white"),
            panel.grid = element_blank(),
            panel.background = element_rect(fill = "black"),
        plot.background = element_rect(fill = "black"),
            legend.position = "none")

This brings us to scale_*_ arguments. They can be very useful but also frustrating. I often use them to change the axes. The main uses of these functions are for changing the axis scale (name, limits, breaks, labels) and specifying specific colors. We already used one such function above (scale_color_discrete()).

Lets first look at scale_*_continuous. We want better axis labels for our plot since right now, we have only two in log form.

10^min(morph$log_wingl)
## [1] 59
10^max(morph$log_wingl)
## [1] 78
# this is the range of our plot

mem_plot1 +
    scale_x_continuous(
        name = "wing length", # change back to just wing length
        breaks = c(log10(60), log10(65), log10(70), log10(75)),
        labels = c(60, 65, 70, 75),
        limits= c(1.77, 1.893)
    )

Lets change the colors of the species. Say we want to use an already existing color palette (there are many of these!). I like using R Color Brewer (we did this in the exploration plot exercise.)

# look at all available palettes in the R color brewer package:
RColorBrewer::display.brewer.all()

# let's use the spectral color
mem_plot1 +
    scale_x_continuous(
        name = "wing length", # change back to just wing length
        breaks = c(log10(60), log10(65), log10(70), log10(75)),
        labels = c(60, 65, 70, 75),
        limits= c(1.77, 1.893))  +
  scale_color_brewer(palette = "Spectral") # why color vs. fill?

#Q: when do you use color vs. fill?

# if you wanted to use a palette with fewer colors than you need, you can first run a function in Rcolorbrewer and specify the number
count_sp <- length(unique(morph$taxon))
getPalette = colorRampPalette(brewer.pal(8, "Set2"))

mem_plot1 +
    scale_x_continuous(
        name = "wing length", # change back to just wing length
        breaks = c(log10(60), log10(65), log10(70), log10(75)),
        labels = c(60, 65, 70, 75),
        limits= c(1.77, 1.893))  + # close to range of values
  scale_color_manual(values = getPalette(count_sp))

        # notice the above changed to manual from brewer

What if you want to specify your own colors? I use color-hex.com. You can add them to your dataset. ut we still want the legend to hav the species names.

taxon <- unique(morph$taxon)
colors_sp <- c(
    "#ff4d00",
    "#e636e1",
    "#78f4b9",
    "#90dcff",
    "#458b74",
    "#ffd6d6",
    "#ff0000",
    "#760300",
    "#b5aba9",
    "#150549")

col_dat <- tibble(taxon, colors_sp)

morph <- merge(morph, col_dat, by = "taxon")

ggplot(morph, aes(log_wingl, log_beakh, color = colors_sp)) +
    geom_point() +
    scale_color_identity()

#this works but where is our legend?
ggplot(morph, aes(log_wingl, log_beakh, color = colors_sp)) +
    geom_point() +
    scale_color_identity(guide = "legend",
                                             labels = c(as.factor(morph$taxon))) +
    labs(color = "Species")

Now lets add plots together. Say we have one for females and one for males (we could also facet and customize, which we will do next. )

10^min(morph$log_beakh)
## [1] 6.7
10^max(morph$log_beakh)
## [1] 16.3
range(morph$log_beakh)
## [1] 0.8260748 1.2121876
morph_females <- morph %>%
    filter(sex == "F")

female_plot <- 
    ggplot(morph_females, aes(log_wingl, log_beakh)) +
    geom_point(color = "green") +
    scale_x_continuous(
        name = "wing length", # change back to just wing length
        breaks = c(log10(60), log10(65), log10(70), log10(75)),
        labels = c(60, 65, 70, 75),
        limits= c(1.77, 1.893))  + # close to range of values
    scale_y_continuous(
        name = "beak heaight", 
        breaks = c(log10(7), log10(9),log10(11),
                             log10(13), log10(15)), 
        labels = c(7, 9, 11, 13, 15),
        limits= c(0.82, 1.22)) +
        theme(
            axis.title = element_text(size = 14, color = "grey50"),
            axis.text = element_text(size = 10, color = "grey50"),
            panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
            panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
            panel.border = element_rect(color = "grey50", fill = NA),
            panel.background = element_rect(fill = NA))

female_plot

# for the male plot, we don't need a y-axis since we are going to place these two plots side-by-side
morph_males <- morph %>%
    filter(sex == "M")

male_plot <- 
    ggplot(morph_males, aes(log_wingl, log_beakh)) +
    geom_point(color = "orange") +
    scale_x_continuous(
        name = "wing length", # change back to just wing length
        breaks = c(log10(60), log10(65), log10(70), log10(75)),
        labels = c(60, 65, 70, 75),
        limits= c(1.77, 1.893))  + # close to range of values
    scale_y_continuous( # include this so plots on same scale
        name = "beak heaight", 
        breaks = c(log10(7), log10(9),log10(11),
                             log10(13), log10(15)), 
        labels = c(7, 9, 11, 13, 15),
        limits= c(0.82, 1.22)) +
        theme(
            axis.title.x = element_text(size = 14, color = "grey50"),
            axis.text.x = element_text(size = 10, color = "grey50"),
            axis.title.y = element_blank(),
            axis.text.y = element_blank(),
            axis.ticks.y = element_blank(),
            panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
            panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
            panel.border = element_rect(color = "grey50", fill = NA),
            panel.background = element_rect(fill = NA))

male_plot

To put plots together, I use the patchwork library. I find it the least tedious. Its documentation is here: https://patchwork.data-imaginist.com/. We have to specify the margin of each plot if we little to no space in between plots. We can also add a title.

plot1 <- female_plot +
    theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 14, hjust = 0.5, 
                                                                    face = "bold", color = "green"),
                plot.margin = unit(c(0.2, 0, 0.2, 0.2), "in")) +
    annotate(geom = "text", label = "(a)", x = 1.77, y = 1.22) +
    annotate(geom = "text", label = "females", x = 1.83, y = 1.22,
                     color = "green", size = 5, fontface = "bold")


plot2 <- male_plot +
    theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 14, hjust = 0.5, 
                                                                    face = "bold", color = "orange"),
                plot.margin = unit(c(0.2, 0.2, 0.2, 0), "in")) +
    annotate(geom = "text", label = "(b)", x = 1.77, y = 1.22) +
    annotate(geom = "text", label = "males", x = 1.83, y = 1.22,
                     color = "orange", size = 5, fontface = "bold")

plot_mem <- plot1 + plot2

ggsave(plot_mem,
             file = "plot_mem.png",
             width = 10,
             height = 5,
             units = "in")

plot_mem

Lets pretend we faceted this plot and we want the same result.

mem_plot_facet <- 
    ggplot(morph, aes(log_wingl, log_beakh, color = sex)) +
    geom_point() +
    facet_wrap(~ sex) +
    scale_color_manual(values = c("green", "orange")) +
    scale_x_continuous(
        name = "wing length", # change back to just wing length
        breaks = c(log10(60), log10(65), log10(70), log10(75)),
        labels = c(60, 65, 70, 75),
        limits= c(1.77, 1.893))  + # close to range of values
    scale_y_continuous( # include this so plots on same scale
        name = "beak heaight", 
        breaks = c(log10(7), log10(9),log10(11),
                             log10(13), log10(15)), 
        labels = c(7, 9, 11, 13, 15),
        limits= c(0.82, 1.22)) +
        theme(
            axis.title = element_text(size = 14, color = "grey50"),
            axis.text = element_text(size = 10, color = "grey50"),
            panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
            panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
            panel.border = element_rect(color = "grey50", fill = NA),
            panel.background = element_rect(fill = NA),
            legend.position = "none",
            strip.background = element_blank(),
            strip.text = element_blank(),
            panel.spacing = unit(0.25, "lines"))

mem_plot_facet

# create a little dataset for text

female_text <- tibble(log_wingl = 1.83,
                                            log_beakh = 1.22,
                                            lab = "females",
                                            sex = factor("F", levels = c("F", "M")))

a_lab <- tibble(log_wingl = 1.77,
                                            log_beakh = 1.22,
                                            lab = "(a)",
                                            sex = factor("F", levels = c("F", "M")))

male_text <- tibble(log_wingl = 1.83,
                                        log_beakh = 1.22,
                                        lab = "males",
                                        sex = factor("M", levels = c("F", "M")))

b_lab <- tibble(log_wingl = 1.77,
                                log_beakh = 1.22,
                                lab = "(a)",
                                sex = factor("M", levels = c("F", "M")))


mem_plot_facet_title <- mem_plot_facet +
    geom_text(data = female_text, label = "females", size = 5) +
    geom_text(data = a_lab, label = "(a)", color = "black",
                        fontface = "bold") +
    geom_text(data = male_text, label = "males", size = 5) +
    geom_text(data = b_lab, label = "(b)", color = "black",
                        fontface = "bold")

ggsave(mem_plot_facet_title,
             file = "mem_plot_facet_title.png",
             width = 10,
             height = 5,
             units = "in")
